Kubernetes QoS Classes - Why They Matter?
Not all Pods are treated equally.

Kubernetes assigns a Quality of Service (QoS) class to every Pod based on its CPU and memory requests/limits.

There are 3 classes:
ðŸŸ¢ Guaranteed
âžœ Requests = Limits for CPU & Memory (for every container)
âžœ Most protected during node resource pressure
âžœ Least likely to be evicted

ðŸŸ¡ Burstable
âžœ Requests < Limits (or mixed requests/limits)
âžœ Can use more when available, but has less eviction protection than Guaranteed

ðŸ”´ BestEffort
âžœ No CPU/memory requests or limits
âžœ Lowest eviction protection
âžœ Often first to be evicted under node pressure

ðŸ’¡ Why this matters: During node pressure (commonly memory pressure), QoS helps you estimate which Pods are most likely to be evicted - BestEffort first, then Burstable, then Guaranteed.

No requests/limits = no resource guarantees.

If your workload is critical, set realistic requests and (where appropriate) limits. Thatâ€™s how you improve stability in production.
